g Tutankhamun, who was murdered at the age of 19.  When he read Howard Carter's description of the tomb's discovery, he felt immediately that his story didn't add up.  'It didn't make sense.  I realised it couldn't have been the way he told it.' says Gerald. 'The first thing I looked at was the Mummy's curse (which supposedly brought terrible consequences for people who entered the tomb).  No one put curses on the tombs of Pharoahs 3000 years ago.<br><br>'When you look at the 20-odd people who were supposedly killed by the curse, many died in mysterious circumstances.  They knew more than they should and had to be silenced.'<br><br>There are other, more concrete facts, like a gold signet ring said to have come from the tomb, which had been on the market for six years in 1922 when it was given to the head of the Metropolitan Museum in New York.  'How did it get there if the tomb hadn't been unearthed' says Gerald.<br><br>Carter claimed that the tomb had already been plundered when he found it. In Egyptian law, that meant he was entitled to 50 per cent of the treasures.  If the tomb had been intact, it all would have gone to the state.<br><br>However, Gerald maintains that Carter was the first man to enter the tomb.  'Some chariots found in the tomb had axles which were 7ft 6in wide, but the entrance was only 5ft 6in wide.  Carter sawed off the wheels and blamed this on Oriental carelessness, yet these people were not careless.<br><br>'I maintain that what people think is the entrance is actually the exit.  The entrance is via another tomb.  Carter also built a false wall to corroberate his story.  He painted it, but the scale of the painting doesn't match that on the other walls.<br><br>'It was an oversight, rather like the axles.  Even so, I think Carter did a hell of a job.  But there were flaws and, sooner or later, the truth will come out.'<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valig